<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FFC7F2F0054F0624" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FFC7F2F0054F0624" blockId="12.[98,1306,3245,3486]" lastBlockId="12.[1367,2580,719,3470]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
Rory’s pseudantechinus was first distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FCEEF2F00B740C7A" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[845,1084,3329,3358]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FB27F2F00A520C7A" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[1156,1306,3329,3358]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">P. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
in 1990 when specimens were examined after a survey of fauna at Woodstock Station in the central Pilbara. Significant skull differences were observed among this newly recognized species and the other two pseudantechinuses (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FCE6F2830C930CF7" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[837,987,3442,3475]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">P. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FBBCF2830A430CF7" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1055,1291,3442,3475]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
) in the region. Unless seen together, the three species are difficult to distinguish externally, but P. rory: evidently differs from the other two partially sympatric species by being smaller in almost all external characters. Morphological and (allozyme) genetic studies from the descriptive study confirmed specific differences, although only one of 53 loci (2%) in a sample of eleven individuals was fixed among populations and overall genetic differentiation was low. Later genetic work (direct DNA sequencing) cast the validity of this species into doubt. There are currently six recognized species of dasyurid marsupial “false antechinuses:” 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F991FCEF09CF025B" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[1586,1671,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F93EFCEF0821025B" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1693,1897,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F8DCFCEF08A5025B" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1919,2029,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F7A7FCEF073D025B" box="[2052,2165,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F728FCEF078D025B" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[2187,2245,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">roryi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F6BEFCEF06C7025B" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[2333,2447,798,831]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">woolleyae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F606FCEF0A8B0202" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9AEFCB409330202" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1549,1659,837,870]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
were initially placed under the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F739FCB406630202" box="[2202,2347,837,870]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
, along with 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F67AFCB4090602EA" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">Parantechinus apicalis</taxonomicName>
. G. H. H. Tate then erected a new genus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F709FC8006CA02EA" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[2218,2434,881,910]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
) for both 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FAF8FC69096E02D1" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1371,1574,920,949]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9C8FC69099102D1" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1643,1753,920,949]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
and a monotypic genus, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F792FC6907A102D1" box="[2097,2281,920,949]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
, for 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F68AFC6906C002D1" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2345,2440,920,949]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
, but then W. D. L. Ride returned them all to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F8C1FC4D08BB02B9" box="[1890,2035,956,989]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
. P. A. Woolley examined penile morphology of Ride’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9F0FC1209AB0560" box="[1619,1763,995,1028]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
supergroup and proposed that 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F702FC1206250560" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[2209,2413,995,1028]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F6DEFC1206990560" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[2429,2513,995,1028]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, the undescribed “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9BEFBFA09C70548" box="[1565,1679,1035,1068]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
,” and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F948FBFA08020548" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1771,1866,1035,1068]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
formed a distinct group. So M. Archer resurrected both of Tate’s genera, placing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F8B8FBC308AE0537" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1819,2022,1074,1107]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F7E0FBC307FB0537" box="[2115,2227,1074,1107]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
” under 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F691FBC3054F0537" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[2354,2567,1074,1107]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FA3EFBAB0AB9051F" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[1437,1521,1114,1147]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F99CFBAB09D6051F" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1599,1694,1114,1147]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
under 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F8AFFBAB088D051F" box="[1804,1989,1114,1147]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
. Direct DNA sequencing of mtDNA and nDNA conducted over the last decade suggests that 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F7E6FB7007F505C6" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[2117,2237,1153,1186]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">P. bilarni</taxonomicName>
is very different genetically from 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FA57FB5D09E405AD" box="[1524,1708,1196,1225]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F967FB5D080205AD" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1732,1866,1196,1225]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
) and all other species of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F760FB5D06D105AD" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[2243,2457,1196,1225]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F60FFB5D0ADE0595" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">P. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
was resolved as sister to all congeners; and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F7ABFB2107D70595" box="[2056,2207,1232,1265]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">P. ningbing</taxonomicName>
was resolved as sister to a clade containing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9F0FB0609AD047C" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1619,1765,1271,1304]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">P. mimulus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F95BFB0608A1047C" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1784,2025,1271,1304]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F79EFB0607D2047C" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[2109,2202,1271,1304]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">P. roryi</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F6D1FB060687047C" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[2418,2511,1271,1304]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">P. roryi</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FAF9FAD609020424" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1370,1610,1319,1344]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
were not monophyletic; rather, they formed a clade with evidence of marked genetic differentiation across their combined geographical distributions. Importantly, the pattern of differentiation in genetics does not match either the purported geographical or morphological boundaries of the two species. Instead, DNA data exhibit breaks consistent with populations in the Cape Range, Barrow Island, and Abydos-Woodstock areas of the Pilbara in Western Australia. Indeed, in Abydos-Woodstock, genetically distinct groups may occur in sympatry but in different microhabitats. Other work has hinted at similar subdivisions farther east in the Sedimentaries and Tanami Desert. More detailed sampling (with associated collection of voucher specimens) is required throughout distributions of these species to determine if genetic boundaries are consistent with variation within or between species. Genetic results are striking, but in recognition of outstanding knowledge gaps in population genetic structure and because taxonomic changes required likely extend beyond a simple submersion of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FA67F8EE0AB50624" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[1476,1533,1823,1856]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">roryi</taxonomicName>
under 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9C7F8EE08780624" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1636,1840,1823,1856]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, the existing taxonomyis retained here. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FAF8F8B708410962" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="distribution">
<caption id="36A6665FFFA52448FAF8F8B708410962" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6608158" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6608158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6608158/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" targetBox="[1364,1956,296,710]" targetPageId="12">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FAF8F8B708410962" blockId="12.[1367,2580,719,3470]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FAF8F8B709430603" bold="true" box="[1371,1547,1862,1895]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Distribution.</emphasis>
Western Australia, from Cape Range on the W coast and through the Pilbara region, N of the Hamersley Range E to the Clutterbuck Hills, 200 km W of the Western Australian/Northern Territory border, and on Barrow I. Rory’s Pseudantechinus is sympatric over the S &amp; W partofits distribution with its congener, Woolley’s Pseudantechinus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9C2F81809B50962" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[1633,1789,2025,2054]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">£. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FAF8F7FE08A40B49" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="description">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FAF8F7FE08A40B49" blockId="12.[1367,2580,719,3470]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FAF8F7FE09110948" bold="true" box="[1371,1625,2063,2092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 8:3-9 cm (males) and 7.7-9 cm (females), tail 6-6 8.8 cm (males and females); weight 19-32 g (males) and 17-26 g (females). Fur of Rory’s Pseudantechinus is reddish; face and chin are tan with dark basal hairs. There is a bright orange patch behind the ears. Tail is distinctly bicolored, and its upper surface is tan and it is paler to white below. Rory’s Pseudantechinus is generally a brighter reddish-brown dorsally than the other species of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F78AF72106480995" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[2089,2304,2256,2289]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
. Rory’s Pseudantechinus and the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F846F7060793087C" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[2021,2267,2295,2328]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
) share the following characteristics: three upper premolar teeth, with the third having a crown area less than two-thirds that of the second premolar; usually two pairs of lower premolar teeth; females have six nipples; and accessory erectile tissue of males forms an appendage to the penis. This combination of characteristics differentiates these two species from all congeners. Despite the similarities, Rory’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F814F64D07ED08B9" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1975,2213,2492,2525]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
tends to have redderfur, is smaller in size, and has a tail that more gradually broadens at the base and is more bicolored than the Fat-tailed 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F95BF5FD08A00B49" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1784,2024,2572,2605]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FAFEF5C2074A0AD3" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FAFEF5C2074A0AD3" blockId="12.[1367,2580,719,3470]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FAFEF5C20A840B30" bold="true" box="[1373,1484,2611,2644]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Habitat.</emphasis>
Variety of habitats from very open low woodland through sand plains dominated by spinifex (7riodia, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F978F5AB08060B1F" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[1755,1870,2650,2683]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
) to large granite rock piles. Rory’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F6EEF5AB0AC60BC6" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
is most abundant around granite tors (large, free-standing rock outcrops) on sand plains. A female with young was dug out of a termite mound, and several others were trapped close to termite mounds. Rory’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F80BF52107DE0B95" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1960,2198,2768,2801]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
has been caught in Elliott and pitfall traps; males and females have been collected during all months of the year. The holotype was taken from low, open woodland of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F7EFF4EE07EA0A24" box="[2124,2210,2847,2880]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Acacia</taxonomicName>
pyrifolia, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F680F4EE06EC0A24" box="[2339,2468,2847,2880]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
(2-3 m tall, 3% canopy cover), 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F913F4B7084C0A03" box="[1712,1796,2886,2919]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Hakea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Hakea</taxonomicName>
subarea, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F822F4B707520A03" box="[1921,2074,2886,2919]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Proteales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Proteaceae</taxonomicName>
(2-3 m tall, less than 0-5% canopy cover), and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F9A6F49F09CE0AEB" box="[1541,1670,2926,2959]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">Acacia sp.</taxonomicName>
(2-3 m tall, less than 0-5% canopy cover) extending over 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448F619F49F055C0AEB" box="[2490,2580,2926,2959]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Triodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Triodia</taxonomicName>
spp-, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FA0BF46709600AD3" box="[1448,1576,2966,2999]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
(c.0-5 m tall, 80% canopy cover).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FAFDF44C066B0ABA" box="[1374,2339,3005,3038]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FAFDF44C066B0ABA" blockId="12.[1367,2580,719,3470]" box="[1374,2339,3005,3038]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
